I visited City Tamale when I flew into NYC from Tennessee for a job interview in South Bronx through a snow storm back in January 2020. The way things worked out was that, right after having some delicious tamales at City Tamale, I got a call from the employer asking me if I can come in earlier for the interview, which I said yes. I had one of the most meaningful interviews with the employer and I ended up getting the job on the spot. Unfortunately, with pandemic and personal circumstances, I didn’t end up working with the employer but I made my big move to NYC regardless and I’m glad I took the big leap of faith. The delicious meal I had at City Tamale was one of the unexplainable things that led me to move to NYC and I’m thankful for that. I wish you guys are making it and staying safe. Best of luck and I hope to make it back there soon.

Heard about this place for a long time and have always wanted to give it a try. This place is in the Hunt's Point section of the Bronx which is all industrial with tons of manufacturing and automotie businesses in the area. Getting here, particularly crossing the Bruckner, can be challenging as every crossing point seems to be flooded with trucks blockig intersections.Lots of cars are double and even trple parked throughout the streets. This place is on the main street of Oak Point Avenue which has a few angled parking strips nearby, which makes parking easy..and free...if you can find a spot. I visited in the eary afternoon on a Friday and was able to snag the last spot. Right now there is only outdoor seating and takeout only due to COVID. This place has a variety of dishes including a hot food tables (chicken, rice, pork...), empanadas and tamales of course. I got a few tamales and empanadas. Everything was very good. They were some of the best tamales and empanadas I've had. What really impressed me was the amount of filling (chicken, pork, veggies..) that were stuffed into the tamales and empanadas. My olny gripe is the price... I think $3+ per tamale may be a tad too much. I can go to Queens or Uptown Manhattan and get some great tamales for $1-$2 each. I would love to return to visit and try some other tamale varieties and even some hot food there.

I don’t know where some of these negative comments are coming from but I must say this place rocks. First of all Tamales aren’t supposed to be huge, so to the guy that said the price and size of the tamales were not worth it, doesn’t know what he’s talking about.  These are definitely authentic, super tasty and I would eat here everyday kind of tamales. I have tried several different ones and I’m never disappointed. The salsa verde tamales are my favorite. My girls love the pork tamales. I have always had a positive experience each time I visit. Ever since I heard about Tamale City, it’s been my favorite tamale spot!!!!! Best ever.

The tamales are good but for the price tag they lack the size and filling. I love their cheese tamales but it’s a dollar over priced and it has a little slice of cheese; their habanero tamales are good too, but once again, not for the price, they’re too small, therefore it’s discouraging  to make the trip when I can get cheaper food from street vendors or more bang for my buck at a corner deli without breaking the bank and more satisfaction. If they were cheaper they would be making a killing, like the dollar pizza joints. I’d eat there all the time if it were cheaper for the tamales alone, the pastelitos aren’t that great either, the taste wasn’t good and it was cold and didn’t have enough meat. I go there when ever I want a good tamale de rajas con queso because they are really good and have great taste, i haven’t tried anything else but their tamales and that one disappointing chicken pastelito. Plus the employee almost gave my credit card to another person while I was still in front of him and of course the other person would gladly take something that isn’t even his, they need to be more focused, it wasn’t even busy. I still give you guys a good rating because I want you guys to succeed and thrive. You guys are the only Mexican spot in the area and I’m sure the rest of the food is good, but if the tamales are to be the holy grail here, then they need to be made with such standard.
